wrote:
> Rik wrote:
> 
> > At 08:32 AM 4/25/2002 -0700, you wrote:
> > >I'm planning on turning my '78 Bus into a camper
> and I was wondering if
> > >there are any reference materials, books,
> magazines on the types of
> > >options available? Can I buy after-market option
> or do I just cannibalize
> > >old buses and make it fit?
> >
> > I suggest you do your own thing.  Use some stock
> Westy stuff, make some things,
> > and use some over the counter things that never
> came stock.  Unless of
> > course, you
> > can afford that English camper interior you've
> been told about.  Nice!
> >
> > Well, personally, I've got a stock '70 Westy, and
> the layout isn't all that
> > great.
> > The icebox is tiny, front opening, and basically
> useless.  The later
> > refrigerators,
> > so I've heard endlessly, are nothing but trouble. 
> Following Bob Hoover's
> > advice
> > (he hangs out for weeks down in Baja) I got a
> super-insulated Igloo
> > cooler--not the
> > un-insulated sort available everywhere.  The
> cooler can now be taken out of
> > the bus,
> > as well as used as a seat (with appropriate sized
> cushion) at the table.
> >
> > The rear facing seat (on a '70) is slightly too
> small for a porta-potty, so
> > I'm going to
> > make a near duplicate that isn't.
> >
> > Curtains are better held in place with rare earth
> magnets sown into the seams,
> > than the stock aluminum tracks with little plastic
> thingees sliding in
> > them, and snaps.
> >
> > The stock things I'd use are the folding bed with
> storage underneath (or a
> > Z-bed),
> > the folding table, and the shelf above the bed. 
> If your passenger seat
> > swivels around
> > to face the rear, as the later Westies did, then
> use the later style table
> > to take advantage
> > of this seat.  If not, then use the early table
> position, and put an early
> > loaf sink/water supply/
> > ice cooler cabinet behind the passenger seat, but
> replace the ice cooler
> > with storage
> > cabinets.  Aside from those, you can really do
> better going non-stock.
> >
> > Bob Hoover discussed his thoughts on the
> matter--he lives in his bus a
> > lot--somewhere
> > or other in his writings, which you can find here:
> >
> > http://osf02.ktu.edu.tr/~ulutas/hoover/
> >
> > Happy trails.
> >
> > Rik                                               
>          Searchlight casting
> > '70 Westy "The Carcass"                           
>  for faults in the
> > ...........be on the road in no time.             
>  clouds of
> > delusion.   R. Hunter
